dsDescriptionValue.value:
The revised UCLA Loneliness Scale is a 20-item self-report measure of levels of loneliness that occur in every day lives of respondents. The construct is related to several personality characteristics including low self-esteem, shyness, feelings of alienation, external locus of control and a belief that the world is not a just place. Among students and older adults loneliness is linked to boredom, restlessness, unhappiness and dissatisfaction with social relationships.

In CAPS/86, the s cale was administered to CAPS respondents and to a same-sex friend. This file contains the CAPS respondents' data. Friends' data are in FLONELY1.

See codebook for additional information

publicationCitation.value: Russell, Dan, Peplau, Letitia and Cutrona, Carolyn E. 'The Revised UCLA Loneliness Scale: Concurrent and Discriminant Validity Evidence.' Journal of Personality and Social Psychology 1980 39(3): 472-480.
